{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600532/1930113001/0433.xml":{"full_text":"News of Markets\nPages 1 to 5\nPart 6\u201412 Paget\nNATIONAL, CAPITAL\nREPORTS BIG DROP\nIN BANK CLEARINGS\nNovember Total $102,030,-\n387, Against $120,261,737\nin Same Month in 1929.\nCOMMITTEEMEN NAMED\nFOR BANKERS\u2019 PARLEY\nPotomac Electric Issue Most Active\nStock in Week End Trading\non D. C. Exchange.\nBank clearings in the National Cap\nital in November totaled $102,030,387.27\nIn comparison with $120,261,737.69 in\nNovember 1929, according to the\nmonthly report ol the Washington\nClearing House Association, available\nat the close of business yesterday. This\nis a decline of $18,231,350.42.\nClearings in Washington. in October\namounted to $118,084,915.34. Total\nclearings for the first 11 months of the\npresent year stand at $1,200,034,523.91,\nagainst $1,365,316,098.74 in the corre\nsponding period in 1929.\nClearings for the same 11 months in\n1928 totaled $1,305,744,189.67, and in\n1927 reached the sum of $1,262,316,-\n174.58. Checks, therefore, passing\nthrough the Washington Clearing\nHouse this year will not equal the\nnumber for the past three years. Local\nhearings in December last year amount\ned to $116,074,630.10, which makes it\neasy to estimate about what the total\nfigure for 1930 will be.\nWhile retail trade in Washington at\npresent is better than it was a year\nago at this time, according to reports\nfrom the Federal Reserve Board, the\ntotal business being transacted here is\nlower. This is true in practically every\nother important city in the country.\nFollowing is a compilation of bank\nclearings in Washington, by months,\nduring the year to date, compared with\nthe corresponding months a year ago:\nMonth. 1930. 1929.\nJanuary $118,219,262 *129,438.291\nFebruary 96.545.212 109,649,040\nMarch 114.113.698 131,795,928\nApril 118.036,652 129,300.050\nMay 113,055,037 126,836.189\nJune 116.280,346 124.028.347\nJuly 109,420,638 127,497,771\nAuauat 96,379,442 113,553,519\nSeptember 97,868.931 114.986,938\nOctober 118.084.915 137.968,361\nNovember 102.030.387 120,261.737\nTotals *1.200,034.523 *1,365.316.098\nAs December is one of the best\nmonths in the year for business, the\nslump in clearings is certain to be con\nsiderably reduced when the final 1930\nfigures are compared with the 1929\nrecords.\nCox to Handle Transportation.\nFrederick H. Cox. cashier of the Com\nmercial National Bank, was appointed\nyesterday by General Chairman F. P.\nH. Siddons to be chairman of the Trans\nportation Committee for the 1931 bank\ners\u2019 convention.\nMr. Cox was born in Fauquier\nCounty, Va., attended the public schools\nin his home town, graduated from the\nManassas High Bchool, and studied at\nthe University of Virginia. He is a\ngraduate of Washington Chapter, Ameri\ncan Institute of Banking.\nHis activities in the District Bankers\u2019\nAssociation have been many. He is at\npresent chairman of the safe deposit\nsection, has been a member of the audi\ntors section and on the Publicity Com\nmittee. Last year and the year before\nhe was chairman of the Committee on\nStandard Banking Forms. This year\nhe is chairman of the Insurance Com\n\u2022L mittee, which aims to work out closer\nI co-operation with the District Life\nf Underwriters\u2019 Association.\nMr. Cox has also done considerable\nwork for previous conventions. In 1927\nhe served on the Press Committee, in\n1928 was vice chairman of the Sports\nCommittee, chairman of that commit\ntee in 1929, and member of the Enter\ntainment Committee in 1930.\nHillyer Made Vice Chairman.\nIt was also announced yesterday that\nBdward L. Hillyer, vice president and\nassistant trust officer of the Union\nTrust Co., has been appointed vice\nchairman of the Transportation Com\nmittee. He was a member of the asso\nciation\u2019s Publicity Committee in 1926-\n27, Fdaudulent Securities Committee in\n1927-28. chairman Auditors\u2019 Section\nCommltee in 1928-29. also a member\nof the Fraudulent Securities and Pro\ntective Committees the same year.\nIn connection with conventions. Mr.\nHillyer has served on the Bports, Hotel\nand Transportation Committees. He\nis a native of Washington, holds a\nmaster\u2019s degree from the National Law\nSchool and Is a member of the District\nof Columbia Bar. He has been with\nthe trust company since it opened in\n1900. is vice president of the Washing\nton Stock Exchange and a member of\nthe Chevy Chase Club.\nLocal Securities More Active.\nSaturday trading on the Washington\nStock Exchange was more active than\nusual. Potomac Electric Power 54 per\ncent preferred was the most active is\nsue. The day\u2019s sales:\nGeorgetown Gas ss\u2014sl,ooo at 103.\nPotomac Electric cons. 5s \u2014$1,000 at\n103.\nWashington Gas 6s A \u2014sl,ooo at 103.\nWashington Railway Electric 4551,000\n$l,OOO at BV/ a SSOO at 87*4-\nCapital Traction Co.\u2014lo at 494, 10\nat 49 Vs. 15 at 49. 10 at 49.\nPotomac Electric 6 per cent preferred\n\u20145 at 111.\nPotomac Electric 54 per cent pre\nferred\u20146o at 107, 10 at 107. 10 at 107,\n10 at 107, 10 at 107, 10 at 107.\nFederal-American Co. common\u2014lo at\n294.\nLa ns ton Monotype\u20143o at 105, 10 at\n105.\nPeoples Drug Stores preferred\u2014lo\nat 99.\nWashington Gas 6s \"B\u201d \u2014$1,000 at 105.\nPotomac Electric 54 per cent pre\nferred\u2014s at 107, 5 at 107.\nBankers Visit Baltimore.\n\u2022dembers of the Washington chapter,\nAmerican Institute of Banking, bowl\ning team, visited Baltimore last evening\nto battle with Baltimore chapter. Be\nfore the contests, the bowlers, board of\nSvemors and officers of the local chap\nwere dinner guests of their hosts.\nThe bowlers defending the local chap\nter\u2019s interests Included Thomas Howard,\nArthur Doing, George Scheinhaut, A. O.\nDooley, Ellsworth Meyer, Kenneth\nBrooks, Joseph D. Yerkes and Holmead\nCallan. Substitutes included William\nRestorff, Frank M. Perley, Robert A.\nSisson, A. E. Henze and William A.\nCady.\nVote on Proposed Sale.\nNEW YORK. November 29 (fP)- \u2014A\nspecial meeting of stockholders of\nMichigan Steel Corporation will be held\nDecember 22 to vote on the proposed\n\u25a0ale of the company's assets to the Na\n_ Uonal Steel Corporation and lmmedl-\nT ate distribution of the proceeds to\nSteal stockholders.\nHe\u2019s 80 Years Old\nI. A. FLEMING,\nFinancial writer for more than six\ndecades, who has reached another mile\nstone in a most unusual career. He still\ncontributes weekly articles on finance\nto The Star.\nFLEMING OBSERVES\nHIS 80TH BIRTHDAY\n\u201cPop\u201d Is Well Known and\nAffectionately Regarded\nin Financial Circles.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nI. A. Fleming, former financial editor\nof The Star and probably the oldest\nwriter on finance in the United States,\nwas 80 years old yesterday.\nIn honor of the unusual event he\nhas invited his newspaper and banker\nfriends to a reception at his home.\n2700 Connecticut avenue, from 5 to 7\nthis evening.\nMr. Fleming has had a most re\nmarkable career as a newspaper man,\nhaving been an active journalist for\nmore than 60 years. Bom in Chicago\non November 29, 1850, he lived there\nfor 53 years, and for 30 years stood\nin the front rank of Chicago\u2019s finan\ncial writers. \u201cPop,\u201d as he is addressed\nby his close friends, was only 15 years\nof age when he began his career of\npreparing newspaper copy, handling\ngrain quotations on what is now the\nChicago Board of Trade. His ability\nand energy rapidly asserted themselves,\nand his inside knowledge of the intri\ncate workings of the grain and stock\nmarkets soon brought him into promi\nnence.\nOnce Star Athlete.\nIn his younger days \"Pop\u201d was very\nfond of sports and in the \u20197os was a\nstar base ball and foot ball player,\nbeing an athlete over 6 feet tall and\nweighing 197 pounds. He was a per\nsonal friend of \"Pop\u201d Anson and \u201cBilly\u201d\nSunday and other diamond kings of\nmany years ago, his semi-professional\nclub often coming in contact with the\nprofessionals. He played against Anson,\nand Charles Comiskey played on a\nteam which Mr. Fleming managed, the\nLiberties. Net to this day has he lost\nhis interest in the fortunes of the two\nChicago major league clubs, although\nhis allegiance has naturally been trans\nferred to the Washington Senators.\nIn the light of the recent popularity\nof night foot ball. It is interesting to\nnote that Mr. Fleming arranged the\nfirst night gridiron contest ever played\nin the Chicago coliseum, between In\ndiana and Wisconsin Universities, the\ngame being played for the benefit of\nthe two colleges.\nDuring his long career in newspaper\nwork in Chicago, Mr. Fleming made\nmany friends among the captains of\nfinance and obtained scores of news\nstories ahead of other less alert finan\ncial writers. In those days the elder\nArmour and Marshall Field were at the\nheight of their fame. Probably the\nmost memorable \u201cnews beat\u201d Mr. Flem\ning ever secured was the first story\nbringing to public attention the famous\nLelter $10,000,000 corner in wheat 20\nor more years ago. News regarding the\n\u201coomer\u201d followed some of the most\nsensational trading sessions ever wit\nnessed on the Chicago Grain Exchange,\nand Mr. Fleming\u2019s information about It\nwas flashed to all parts of the world.\nObtained Other \"News Beats.\u201d\nThe sensational speculation of the\nMoore brothers was another famous\nstory which Mr. Fleming covered alone\nfor the Chicago Journal. W. H. and\nT. H. Moore were corporation lawyers\nand started a bull movement in Dia\nmond Match and New York Biscuit. It\nwas in 1896. Match was pushed up to\n225 a share and Biscuit to 180 and 200.\nTrading became so wild that the Chi\ncago Stock Exchange was closed until\nsettlements could be made which pre\nvented the fall of many financial\nhouses. In the final adjustments it was\nreported in Chicago at the time that\nthe sponsors of the stocks had lost $15,-\n000,000. a very large sum in those days.\nLeaving Chicago, Mr. Fleming became\neditor of the Minneapolis Times. The\npaper was suddenly bought by another\npaper and Mr. Fleming next found him\nself writing for a syndicate of trade\npapers. Coming to Washington he rep\nresented for a time 28 of these papers.\nAfter he had become well established\nhere, his former employer in Chicago\nhappened to com o here. They met one\nday, unexpectedly, on Pennsylvania\navenue, with the result that the finan\ncial writer Joined the Washington\nTimes staff.\nGuest at Seven Conventions.\nAsked to take the financial editorship\nof The Star when he was 63 years old.\nMr. Fleming considered the offer the\ngreatest tribute of his career and went\nto work on the paper on December 21,\n1913. Since retiring from the dally\nfield some years ago he has kept in\nthe harness by writing Sunday feature\narticles on finance. Mr. Fleming has\nalways had the interests of the Dis\ntrict Bankers\u2019 Association at heart and\nhas been a guest of the organization 1\nat the last seven Conventions. He has\nattended every out-of-town convention\never held by the association, with one\nexception, illness keeping him away\nfrom that one.\nWhile in Chicago Mr. Fleming always\nrepresented the late C. W. Barron,\nowner of the Wall Street Journal, at\nthe annual meetings of many big\ncorporations. Mr. Barron held at least\none share of stock in a host of the\nmost Important corporations in the\nUnited States so that he might always\nhave a representative present to ob\ntain first hand all the annual reports.\nSome of the corporations were not as\nopen in their business methods then\nas they are now and some of these\nmeetings were suddenly adjourned when\nthe officials wdFe presented with proxies\nfrom C. W. Barron, which admitted a\nrepresentative in person.\nCart First Vote for Grant.\nMr. Fleming cast his Jrst ballot for\nGoo. Grant whan ho ratrsor his sooond\n1\nFINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\n\u00ael)c Sunday Star\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 30, 1930.\nSTOCKS DEPRESSED\nBY SHORT SELLERS\nDURING LAST WEEK\nMarket Gives Evidence of\nBeing Thoroughly Liqui\ndated \u2014Averages Firm.\nRAIL LIST BEARS BRUNT\nOF PROFESSIONAL ATTACK\nBank Situation Improves and\nAlarm Over Grain Values\nHas Subsided.\nBY CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November 29.\u20141 tis\neasy to become impatient over the slow\nprogress being made in business and\nmarket conditions and to be apprehen\nsive when, as this week, stocks resume\ntheir downward trend. That we are\ngradually coming up out of the valley of\ndepression is, however, a fact supported\nby evidence in several directions.\nTo illustrate: Copper metal was ad\nvanced to 12 cents a pound after de\nclining 50 per cent. It has fallen back\nto 104 cents, but It holds steadily a\ncent a pound over the low of October.\nFor nearly six weeks the price of iron\nand steel manufactured products has\nbeen maintained at a fixed basis, al\nthough the output of the industry has\ndeclined until it is now 41 per cent of\ncapacity.\nThe textile trade has consolidated its\ngains and is in a relatively good posi\ntion after two years of distress. The\nlatest figures of earnings of the public\nutilities indicate a small increase in\ngross and net over the first nine\nmonths of 1929. Only half the dividend\ncuts reported for October have been\nannounced for November, with none\nthis month as significant as those com\npelled in the earlier period. And, in\nspite of the secondary reaction in securi\nties now taking place, the New York\nStock Exchange figures for November\nwill show a more satisfactory plane of\nvaluations than those of the two previ\nous months.\nBank Situation Improves.\nLast week the Eastern banking com\nmunity was disturbed by the epidemic\nof failures in Tennessee, Kentucky,\nNorth Carolina, Missouri, Indiana and\nIllinois. Some of the institutions that\nclosed have been reopened. A few new\nbut unimportant suspensions have oc\ncurred. A situation in New York that\nhad been giving considerable anxiety\nhas been adjusted through the efforts\nof the New York Clearing House As\nsociation.\nThere has been an absence of the\n\u2019alarms that ran through the grain\ntrades of the United States and Canada\na fortnight ago. Some progress has\nbeen made in stabilizing the oil in\ndustry, though this is far from being\nin a healthy state. Merchants who\nhave been praying for cold weather,\nas the farmers last August petitioned\nfor rain, now have It. It Is a good\naugury for holiday trade. Abroad there\nhas been more wild talk of mora\ntoriums and debt cancellations, but,\nin a quiet way, conversations have been\ngoing on whose importance in inter\nnational finance will be disclosed later.\nRecord Dividend Payments.\nThe dividend and interest payments\nto be made on Monday will exceed\nthose of the same period In other years.\nIt Is the rule, rather than the excep\ntion, to find an industrial company\nwhose current statement shows a\nsmaller inventory than last November.\nFrequently it has a higher proportion\nof cash and marketable securities than\nduring its most prosperous days.\nAs a whole the stock market has\nbeen well liquidated. The pressure\nagainst it in this short business week\nhas been from the professional trader\nand not from the investor. The for.\nmer \u201claid off\u201d for awhile from his\nregular occupation of abusing values\nand gave the Street an opportunity to\nregain part of Its courage. With aver\nage prices recovering about 20 per cent\nof the September-November decline and\ninvestment purchases dropping, he has\nresumed his activity and the rumor\nmill Is again grinding out false state\nments.\nRail Shane Heavily Sold.\nThe point of least resistance In this\nweek\u2019s market has been in railroad\nshares. Each month witnesses a spasm\nof selling of rails as gross and net\nrevenues reveal heavy losses, compared\nwith one and two years ago. The Octo\nber returns are poorer than anticipated.\nIn spite of this great decline in net,\na large proportion of the carriers are\nearning their dividends. Few contem\nplate any change In their payments to\nshareholders In the next six months.\nOnly two Important railroad dividends\nhave been affected In a year, when over\n900 corporation dividends have been\nreduced or passed. And they are\nbalanced by Increased dividends.\nIn the sporting parlance of the sea\nson, the railroads are now down on the\nfive-yard line. Their executives have\ngone \u201cInto a huddle.\u201d They have their\nbacks up. They have plenty of re\nserve strength, but good generalship,\nsome substitutions In the line-up and\nteamwork are necessary if they are\nto win out in the present crisis.\n(Copyright 1930.1\nCHILDS SECURITIES\nCONCERNS CONSOLIDATE\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November 29.\u2014Effec\ntive December 1, C. F. Childs Co.,\ndistributors of United Btates Govern\nment securities, and Childs Securities\nCorporation have fceen consolidated un.\nder the name of C. F. Childs Co.\nC F. Childs, president of the com\nbined organizations, organized C. F.\nChilds Co. in 1905 and with the ex\nception of two and one-half years\u2019\nperiod ending October 10 last, the busi\nness has always been under Mr. Childs\u2019\nmanagement.\nm nr=\nterm In the White House. He also stood\nout in a cold November rain for many\nhours to get a chance to vote for James\nG. Blaine.\nA charter member of the National\nPress Club in this city, he is also a mem\nber of The Evening Star Club and a\nlife member of the Chicago Press Club.\nA brother, John, who lives in Chicago\nand is about 85 years of age, was for\nmany years a business associate of the\nlate Andrew Carnegie. Mr. Fleming\nmakes his home with his daughter-in\nlaw, Mrs. Russell S. Fleming, widow\nof his oldest son, who died In 1916. Mr.\nFleming\u2019s wife died in 1914. Other\nrelatives Include a son, George, residing\nin Chicago.\nAnd as the years go by friends often\nobserve that I. A. Fleming and John\nD. Rockefeller look more and more\nalike. Perhaps, because these \u201cboys\u201d\nboth spend their Winters basking In\nthe Florida sunshine.\nTrade Trend and Outlook\nHenry Ford Believes Business Depression Will Be\nLifted When Basic Commodities Are Obtain\nable at Greatly Reduced Prices\nBY HENRY FORD,\nAs Told to A. M. Smith.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nDETROIT, November 29. \u2014We will\nknow when we have hit the bottom\nof the business depression by the fact\nthat living expenses will become lower\nthan this generation has ever seen them,\nin the opinion of Henry Ford.\n\u2018\u2018That,\u201d said Mr. Ford, \u201cIs going to be\none of the permanent gains of this\nperiod the United States is passing\nthrough\u2014the necessities of life will\nnever cost so much again.\n\u201cYou will know that the depression\nhas begun to lift when you see food and\nclothing, fuel and housing plentifully\nand easily obtainable at greatly re\nduced prices. Nothing except high\nprices of basic commodities is pro\nlonging the depression.\u201d\nMr. Ford said he would not discuss\nthe present situation If he were expect\ned to indulge In the evasion of hard\nfacts.\nDefines Prosperity.\n\u201cSmooth words butter no parsnips,\u201d\nhe said, \u201cand the sooner we begin call\ning a spade a spade the better. Pros\nperity In the United States Is nothing\nmore nor less than the passing of goods\nfrom person to person. Prosperity is\nnot in Treasury balances or bank bal\nances, but In the steady and full ex\nchange of goods. Anything that hinders\nthis destroys prosperity. Anything that\nrestores such exchange restores pros\nperity.\n\u201cProsperity does not even consist In\nthe profit which industry makes. If\nindustry operated without a cent of\nprofit, and the full and steady flow of\ngoods continued, we should still have\nprsperity. The only profit of work,\nafter all, is life. That Is what all our\noperations exist for\u2014they keep life go\ning.\n\u201cMore people see this today than ever\nbefore,, and one immediate result Is\ngoing io be lower prices on all the\nnecessities of life. There can be no\ngreat progress of any kind until the\npeople are assured beyond anxiety of\na low cost of livelihood. We cannot\ngo on exploiting the necessities of life\nand expect any kind of advancement\nin the United States. Making a living\nshould be the easiest thing we do. And\nthe only high-priced commodity we\nhave any right to Is a day\u2019s work; that\nshould never be low priced.\u201d\nMr. Ford was asked if he thought the\ntariff had anything to do with the de\nlayed return of prosperity.\n\u201cAs you know,\u201d he said, \u201cI was\nagainst the tariff. I am essentially a\nfree trader for the Industry of the\nUnited States. We are all big enough\nto forego protection. If there are any\nbusiness interests that wanted the tariff,\nall I can say is that they got It, but\nthey will not get what they expected\nout of It.\nForeign Factories.\n\u201cAt the same time, the tariff has not\nbeen entirely without benefit. It has\nhelped other countries. \u2019When they\nraised their tariff walls against the\nUnited States they made It necessary\nfor American Industry to emigrate and\nbuild factories behind the tariff walls\nand give employment to foreign work\nmen. That 1s going to prove a con-\nDROP IN MARYLAND\nCROPS IS REPORTED\nPeas, Com and Tomatoes Off\nFrom 50 to 75 Per Cent,\nSays Survey.\n3pecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE. November 29. \u2014Peas,\ncom and tomatoes, Maryland\u2019s chief\ncrops for canning, are off from 50 to\n75 per cent this year because of the\ndrought, according to an incomplete\nsurvey just completed by F. M. Shook,\nexecutive secretary of the Tri-State\nPackers\u2019 Association.\nThe yield in peas, the crop hardest\nhit in the Btate, will be about 26.54 per\ncent of last year\u2019s crop, while that of\ncom and tomatoes is indicated to be\n39.97 and 76 per cent, respectively, of\nthe 1929 output, the report states.\nThe association does not gather fig\nures on the string bean crop, as this\nwork is done by the Census Bureau,\nwhich makes a report every two years.\nIt is estimated, however, that the yield\nwill be about 60 per cent of the 1929\nharvest, Mr. Shook said.\nThe low yield of the State\u2019s principal\ncrops is not expected to be reflected\nto any extent in the figures of the coun\ntry as a whole, and will not perceptibly\ninfluence prloes, it was declared.\n\"The decrease in the tomato atop\nwould have been noticeable in the\nnational yield had it not been for the\nfact that the California crop was un\nusually heavy,\u201d Mr. Shook said.\nThe com estimate was based on re\nturns from about 90 per cent of the\nState canners, and that of the tomato\ncrop on returns from some 60 per cent\nof the canners.\nLast year 1,865,000 cas\u00b0s of 24 cans\neach of com were packed and the\ntwnato pack was 4,050,160 cases. In\n1929, 1,469,000 cases of peas were\npacked, as against 399.918 cases this\nyear, despite the fact that additional\nacreage was planted in 1930.\nGRAIN MARKET\nCHICAGO, November 29 (4>).\u2014Grain\nprices turned upward today at the last,\nled by com. Weather conditions over\nthe com oelt were unfavorable for the\nmovement of com to market, and\ncountry offerings were light, with ar\nrivals here greatly reduced and stocks\non hand meager. Besides, a drop of 4\ncents a bushel in com values, com\npared with the week\u2019s high, was gen\nerally looked upon as calling for re\nadjustment.\nCom closed strong, V/ 4 &1% a bushel\nhigher than yesterday\u2019s finish. Wheat\nclosed Irregular, y 4 off to up, oats\nshowing advance and provisions\nunchanged to a rise of 7 cents.\nWHEAT\u2014 High. Low. Close.\nDecember, old .75 .74% ,74%-.74%\nDecember, new.. .76 .74% ,74%-.75\nMarch, old 77% .77% ,77%-.77%\nMarch, new 78 .77% .77%-.77%\nMay, old 78% .79 .79%\nMay, new 80% .79% .79%-.SO\nJuly 78% .74% .75%-.79 Vi\nCORN\u2014\nDecember, 01d... .78% .73% .78%-.75%\nDecember, new.. .78% .73% .78%\nMarch, old 78% .76 .78-.78%\nMarch, new 78% .76% .78V\u00ab-.76%\nMay, old 79% .77% .79%-.79%\nMay. new 80 .78% .79%-.80\nJuly 80% .78% .80%\nOATS\u2014\nDecember, 01d... .34% .33% 34%-.34%\nDecember, new.. .34% .33% -34%\nMarch, old 36% .35% .36%- 36%\nMarch, new 36 .35% .36\nMay. old 37% .36% .37%-.87%\nMay. new 37% .36% .37%\nRYE\u2014\nDecember, 01d... .40% .39% .40%\nDecember, new.. .40% .40 .40%\nMarch, old 43% .43% .43%\nMarch, new 41% .43% .43%\nMar. old -j4% .44|5-.44%\njijjp\nf k. 'sr <K|\nHENRY FORD.\nsiderable factor in the prosperity of\nother countries. And we have got to\ntake a wide view of these matters be\ncause no country is prosperous to itself\nalone: all of us most prosper together,\nelse none of us prospers very much.\n\u201cI have a belief that when anything\nis permitted to occur, on such a scale\nthat it affects the life of the people,\nthere Is usually some good result lurk\ning in it, if you can find it.\n\u201cThe tariff in the United States en\nables the food and clothing and' fuel\nand housing exploiters to keep their\nprices a little higher a little longer, but\nat the same time It creates conditions\nwhich will inevitably bring those prices\ntumbling down.\nCalls Depression Unnecessary.\n\u201cThose people who wanted the tariff\nthought they were doing something in\ntheir own interests; it will turn out that\nunintentionally they were starting forces\nthat will work directly In the interests\nof the people, they thought to exploit.\n\u201cIt is too bad that, our good results\nmust come by such Indirect and costly\nmeans, but they come; there Is no stop\nping them.\n\u201cThis depression was entirely un\nnecessary; but as long as you had a\npopulation believing that they could get\nsomething for nothing, it was Inevitable.\nYet Its value In clarifying the public\nmind Is too great to measure.\n\u201cUnless our people are far less In\ntelligent than I credit them with being,\nthey are through with false leaders, and\nthat means that after this we shall be\nthrough with depressions for a long\ntime. What we are going to get out of\nthis one Is a lower-priced livelihood and\na larger family margin for Investment\nIn permanent things.\u201d\n(Copyright, 1930. by North American News\npaper Alliance.)\nSteel Produce-\nLook for 1 .crease\nIn January Trade\nm\nMills Expected to Step Up\nSchedules With Gain\nin Orders.\nSpecial Diepatch to The Star.\nPITTSBURGH, November 29 \u2014Steel\nproducers quite generally appear to be\nof opinion that the recession in gen\neral business, after allowance for sea\nsonal variations, has about run its\ncourse.\nIn this they are more or less sup\nported by the latest reports on freight\ncar loadings and bank debits, although\nit is somewhat doubtful whether they\nstudy such statistics closely. As a\nmatter of fact, the steel industry Is one\nwhich furnishes material for a large\nmass of statistics and one which does\nnot study even Its own statistics.\nSometimes there is a condition In\nsteel when it seems doubtful whether\nthe existing rate of operation will con\ntinue, there appearing to be a combi\nnation of various classes of consuming\nactivity coming together, any one or\nmore of which may slip. Sometimes\nthere is a condition when all consum\ning lines are doing so poorly that there\nseems to be no chance for anything\nbut an increase.\nThe latter is the condition now, with\nthe exception that there is a rather\nheavy movement of fabricated struc\ntural material, order books of the fabri\ncating shops being fairly well filled,\nwhile the season of year is no more\nthan a small handicap. Everything\nelse is very dull. Even line pipe has\npractically diappeared from the reck\noning, the season being over with cer\ntain relatively small exceptions.\nSteel ingot production has passed\nbelow a 40 per cent rate, and the\nholiday this week was scarcely a factor,\nas it was not a regular steel mill holi\nday. There may not be much further\ndecline in December, except through\nsome plants perhaps closing for the\nweek containing Christmas. There will\nbe an effort to run before that, to pro\nvide Christmas pay rolls. January can\nscarcely fail to show an increase to\n45 or 50 per cent, or even more. It\nhas never been difficult for steel to\nshow increasing demand in the first\ntwo or three months of a year.\nAs to the price situation, it has been\nmade reasonably clear that whatever\nmay be nominal or asking prices in\nfuture, the steel to be shipped during\nthe first quarter of the new year will\nnot net the mills more than prices\nnow being quoted as the market.\n(Copyright, 1930.)\nMONTREAL BANK HAS\n$6,519,031 PROFITS\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nMONTREAL. November 29. \u2014Striking\nevidence of the soundness of underly\ning conditions in Canada is presented\nby the strong statement which the Bank\nof Montreal has forwarded to its stock\nholders, covering operations for the\nfiscal year ended October 31. The profit\nand loss account shows profit of $6,519,-\n031, as compared with $7,070,892 In the\nprevious year.\nBOND INTEREST PAYMENT.\nNEW YORK, November 29 (\u00a3*).\u2014J.\nW. Seligman Co. and the National\nCity Bank of New York, fiscal agents\nfor the republic of Peru, have received\nthe entire amount required for interest\nand sinking fund payments due up* to\nDecember 1, 1930, on Peruvian national\nloan bonds, first and seoond series. Os\nthe first series, $290,000 have been\ndrawn for redemption on December X.\nBETTER SENTIMENT\nIN FOREIGN TRADE\nCIRCLES IS NOTED\nGreater Activity in Steel and\nWool Demand Occurs\nDuring Week.\nCAPITAL MARKETS MOVE\nWITHIN NARROW RANGE\nWage Problems Continue to Prove\nDominant Factor in Euro\npean Countries.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November 29.\u2014Cable\ndispatches to the Business w eek give\nthe following survey of business -oad\nfor the week ending November 29:\nBusiness conditions are without any\nrecognizable trend for better or for\nworse. Sentiment is cheerful, though\nmarkets generally are listless, except\nfor a distinct strengthening of wool de\nt mand and somewhat better activity in\nsteel within the limits characteristic\n-of current volumes. The statistical po\nf sltion of wheat and the prospect for\na record carry-over are cause for some\nconcern. The continued Irregularity of\ncopper is disturbing other metals. So\nfar, developments run true to predlc\ntions that the bottom has passed, but\nthat activity will continue to be irregu\nlarly close to the bottom for at least\nthe greater part of the Winter, with\n1 no appreciable rise expected before\nr Spring.\nMoney Rate*.\n5 Financial conditions are similarly\nunchanged. There is some tightening\nof money, due to day-by-day technical\ncauses. It is forecasted that low rates\nwill continue during the first quarter.\ni Stock markets are weak, and there is\nt little confidence in Wall street lm\ni provement. The Business Week\u2019s Euro\ni pean organization has canvassed inter\nnational stock brokers in the principal\ni countries on reports of European buy\nr ing in Wall street. It is the consensus\nthat there is some buying at recent\nlows, and this is expected to be re\npeated on new price dips: but, so far,\nl all these purchases have been charac\nterized as small Individual orders. The\nlargest reported was $500,000. On the\nother hand, there has been an avid re\nsponse, especially in England, to gilt\nedged issues, but to such issues only.\nConversion operations in England and\nt France still hang fire, but will almost\ncertainly precede any marked revival in\ncapital markets, unless the plan is\n1 completely abandoned.\n1 Probably the direction of the next\nimportant movement of capital will be\ntoward Eastern Europe. This move\nment was Imminent a year ago, when\nit was arrested by the beginnings of the\ndepression. There is discussion again\nof reviving various loans then for\nmulated. but since placed on the shelf\nawaiting favorable conditions. Without\nexception, every Eastern European\ncountry is harboring one or more proj\nects, either of refinancing government\ndebts or public works construction or\nof expansion of agricultural mortgage\nfacilities. In only a few cases are in\ndustrial developments awaiting these\nloans. It is likely that it will be some\ntime, however, before lack of confidence\nis sufficiently overcome to permit\nmoney to respond to these economic\nneeds.\nMeanwhile, the central banks are\nconferring with Basle on the possibili\nties of co-ordinating policies to permit\nbetter redistribution of gold, and estab\n-1 lishment at Basle of a gold and foreign\nexchange clearing house to permit book\ntransfers.\nBritish Wage Situation.\nThe immediate major issue in Great\nBritain continues to be the railway and\ncoal wage questions. No progress has\nbeen made in the conferences this week\nand there is real danger in the mining\nindustry of local stoppages, since miners\nand operators have reached no agree\nment and the present schedule termi\nnates on December 1. The French are\ncheered that October trade showed\nsome seasonal improvement, though it\nis known that improvement was less\nthan elsewhere.\nIn Germany, the Upper House has\npassed all but two minor measures on\nthe Bruening fiscal reform program of\n30 bills. The Reichstag will tackle the\nprogram when it reconvenes December\n3. Meanwhile the price-reduction cam\npaign continues. October indices showed\na further, but less marked, decline in\nIndustrial activity, measured in terms\nof the number of workmen employed in\nmining, metallurgical and chemical\nindustries. Construction contracted.\nWood, paper and textiles remained un\nchanged. Leather, leather products,\nfootwear, paper products and porcelain\nadvanced. Leather showed the largest\ngain, though none was over 5 per cent.\nItalian Salary Slash.\nItaly has followed the German ex\nample and made an even more radical\n12 per cent slash in salaries of govern\nment employes. It is estimated that\nthis will be enough to iron out the an\nticipated budget deficit for the year,\ni Business is now expecting that govem\ni ment pressure will reduce other wages\nand price levels.\nSemi-political strikes in Spain are less\nvigorous, but political conditions are\ni tense, with elections now scheduled for\nMarch. Peseta stabilization is likely to\ni ake place at around 12 cents.\nThe Geneva Economic Conference so\nfar is productive of only an assortment\nof divergent views. Accord under pres\nent world conditions is improbable.\nMARGIN REQUIREMENTS\nREDUCED BY BROKERS\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November 29.\u2014A lead\ning New York Stock Exchange house\nhas announced a reduction in theif\nminimum margin requirements on ac.\ntive stocks listed on the New York\nStock Exchange. This reduction par\nticularly applies to low-priced stocks.\nIt is understood that the firm\u2019s action\nis due to the fact that at present abouf\nhalf of all the active stocks are sell\ning below S4O per share. Under the\nnew schedule, the firm reserves the\nright, as usual, to require a larger\nmargin, in its discretion, on any par\nticular stock or stocks. The new\nschedule becomes effective December\n1 in all the firm\u2019s branches through\nout the country.\nThe new minimum margin require,\nments on stocks listed on the New\nYork Stock Exchange are: $6 per share 4\non stocks selling between 10 and 19%;\n$8 per share on stocks selling between\n20 and 29%; $lO per share on stocks\nselling between 30 and 39%; sl2 per\nshare on stocks selling between 40 and\n493 b\u00bb and 26 per cent of market value\non stocjm selling above SSO. Stocks\nselling wow $lO most be paid in full.\nClassified Ads\nPages 5 to 12\nBusiness News\nin\nRetrospect\nNational Banks Have De\nvoted Considerable Effort\nto Building Up Their\nTrust Business Since Pas\nsage of the McFadden\nAmendment in 1927.\nBY I. A. FLEMING.\nPassage of the McFadden amendment\nin 1937 gave to the national banks the\nprivilege of assuming all the functions\nof a trust company and the right to\nadd \u201cand trust company'\u2019 to the end\nof their official title. The only limita\ntion was the recognition of the rights\nof a State, such laws governing a trust\ncompany\u2019s operation being honored.\nPrior to the McFadden amendment\nnational banks were allowed the same\nrights under limited rules and with re\nnewals, etc. But few banks availed\nthemselves of the early rights under the\nold laws, and with the coming of '27\nthere were great changes to be met,\ngreat wealth had been gained, mighty\ncorporations established and many of\nthem, many individual producers and\nIncorporated, closely held Industrial\nestablishments, decided to put the bur\nden of furnishing their capital upon\nthe public and Issued millions of new\ncommon stocks, which later cluttered\nthe New York market. A veritable rush\nof national Institutions to seek a share\nof the trust company business followed.\nFormerly, the charters of national\nbanks expired every 20 years and had\nto be renewed. We had an experience in\nWashington that demonstrated how one\nman might hold up the charter of a\nbank. Hence there was no assurance\nof permanency in the matter of han\ndling trusts, but this was remedied In\nthe McFadden amendment, the measure\nthat gave real impetus to the banking\nbusiness under national charter.\nThere Is a fly In their ointment and\none that they are anxious to get out\nof their way. Reference Is made to the\ndecision of a New England Federal jus\ntice that the merger of a trust company\nwith a national bank did not give the\nbank the right to function under wills\nand other documents naming the trust\ncompany as trustee and executor, either\nor both.\nAs stated before the Legislatures of\neach State are being urged to rectify\nthis matter at their sessions this Win\nter.\nToday there are 91,000 trusts, more\nor less, being administered by national\nbanks, and at least $4,500,000,000 In\ntheir care, while they are also trustees\nfor $12,000,000,000 of bonds Issued by\ncorporations. They are getting their full\nshares of the business as time passes\nand are working just as hard for the\ndollar of trusts as they ever worked for\nthe dollar of deposits. As a real matter\nof fact, there Is much more profit in\nthe former than the latter In these days\nwhen deposits are difficult to put out at\nsatisfactory rates.\nDifficnH Job.\nThe office of the controller of the\ncurrency has been made to do nearly\ndouble work since the advent of the\nrush of trust company business to\nnational banks.\nThe investment of the billions of\ntrust funds Is one of the most burden\nsome tasks that bankers have, one of\nthe most thankless, one of the hardest.\nThose who have tried making invest\nments on their own account, and their\nname Is legion, will readily recognize\nthe truth of the statement, while thou\nsands of them could not be coaxed to\nenter the security field again\u2014they\nhave not the wherewithal, but a trust\ncompany must make good.\nMany of the companies, the very\nlargest, have worked In harmony In\nthe selection of their Investments, and\nin this way brought the combined judg\nment of many experts to bear upon\ntheir purchases.\nJ. W. Pole, controller of the cur\nrency, will undoubtedly guard closely\nall trust assets and will be especially\nwatchful for national banks in weak\nened condition, for the right to operate\nas trust companies Is broad and many\nbanks in relatively small sectors have it.\nBank Failures.\nMany of the bank failures of todny\nare among the State Institutions that\nshould have closed their doors a year\nago. Many are small institutions In lo\ncalities where It Is a difficult matter to\neven conduct business on a satisfactory\nbasis.\nNo Income Tax Clipping.\nFive times within the last nine years\nIncome taxes have been reduced to\nthe satisfaction of the taxpayer. It\nwould seem that the clipping process in\nso far as Income taxes are concerned\nhas definitely ended. Not only that,\nbut it would be but natural that the\ntrend should take the reverse direc\ntion. For the first quarter of the fis\ncal year the chief sources of Income\nfell off about $40,000 a month, and\nthe ratio for the second quarter would\nbe even heavier, as there has been\nno betterment In business, especially\nIn the producing end. With the fiscal\nyear showing a loss of at least $500,-\n000,000, one may judge that Secretary\nMellon will not advocate a cut, but\nrather that he may have something\nto say regarding an increase.\nCongress Is happy when It Is cutting\nincome taxes, just as the various States\nseem to be pleased when finding some\nthing that they can put under the\nImpost of a tax.\nReal effort Is being made by the\nTreasury Department to Increase the\ncollection of taxes and to secure a\njust report In connection with Incomes.\nFew important statements of Incomes\nare passed and approved in the two.\nyear period provided by law, this neces\nsity being obviated by the Treasury In\nsecuring from the taxpayer an agree\nment extending for an indefinite period.\nIn the case of a taxpayer refusing\nthis consent he is Immediately plas\ntered with a much heavier tax, for the\nburden of proof Is on the debtor.\nGetting after the bootleggers and\nthe racketeers all over the country is\nnot undertaken by the Government\nthrough the Treasury Department to\npunish law violations but to raise\nrevenue, and In the aggregate the\npenalties for non-returns and taxes due\nwill make an Important contribution\nto the Treausry.\nNEW YORK COTTON\nNEW YORK, November 29 (JF). \u2014A\nfurther decline of 9 to 10 points in\ncotton during today's trading seemed\nto attract a little more trade buying\nand considerable week end covering, ana\nwas followed by rallies which carried\nthe price of May contracts up from\n10.96 to 11.10, or 4 points net higher.\nThat delivery closed at 11.09, with the\ngeneral market closing very steady at\nnet advances of 1 to 4 points.\nFutures closed very steady, 1 to 4\nhigher; December, 10.44; January, 10.46.\nNew contracts, December, 10.48al0.50;\nJanuary, 10.59a10.60; March, 10.83;\nMay, ll.09all.10; July, 11.24a11.25;\ndling, 10.60.\nHish. Low. Close.\nJanuary, old 107*1 10.53\nJanuary, new 10.60 *10.46 10.59\nMaroll 10 83 vb 0.70 10 83\nMay 11.10 10 96 11 09\nJulv 11.25 11.13 11.24\naare-sH n m\nPROSPERITY AIDED:\nBY RAPID GROWTH\nOF NEWBUSINESS\nFour Great Industries Added\nto List in Last 20\nYears.\nSTATE TAX COMMISSION\nRECEIVES INDORSEMENT\nConference Board Urges Impor\ntance of Expert Advice on\nBevenue Matters.\nBY JOHN F. SINCLAIR.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, November 29.\u20141 n the\nlast two decades four great Industries\nhave developed. First, the automobile,\nwhich forced an epoch expansion In\nbusiness activity. Next, motion pic\ntures. This industry has developed In\n20 years Into one of the 10 big busi\nnesses cf the world, giving hundred*\nof thousands employment and million*\nof people dally entertainment. Then\nradio came with a bang to supplement\nmotion picture entertainment. And\nelectric refrigeration made the fourth.\nWhat will be the next?\n\"The humidifier,\u201d suggests E. W.\nBrehm, oresldent of the Doherty-\nBrehm Co. of Chicago, whose business\nhas been expanding rapidly during the\nlast 18 months, although other busi\nnesses have been running In low gear.\nAppeal to Home Owner.\n\u201cAnd I\u2019ll tell you why,\u201d continued\nthis round-faced, youthful manufac\nturer. \u201cIt has made an Instant appeal\nto the home owner, who for years ha*\nattempted, without success, to eliminate\nthe devastating effect of dry Winter\nair on his family\u2019s health, his home\nfumishings, the woodwork, floors and\npaneling. Proper humidification of the\nair really brings comfort and health\nfulness Into the home.\n\u201cAt such times as these,\u201d went Otl\nMr. B.ehm, \u201cwhen older Industries are\nfinding it Increasingly difficult to se\ncure Increased buying interest in their\nproducts, It Is the new Item on the\nmarket that often develops new fields\nfor employment, new Jobs for those\nwho have been laid off from the old\nJobs. It Is easy to trace the effect of\nthe automobile, the radio, the motion\npicture, the electric refrigerator. In my\nopinion, the need today 1* alr-condl\ntlonlng and humidification, making the\nhome just as comfortable In the Sum\nmer as In the Winter and making It\njust as healthful Inside a* the fresh\nair outside.\u201d\nIn the Patent Office in Washington\nare thousands of new Inventions for\nwhich there is a need and a demand.\nIf properly promoted, financed and\nmarketed at this time, they would add\nnew Jobs, new businesses and new\nprosperity to the Nation\u2019s total.\nWhat promoter or financier will dig\nin the musty old patent files and bring\nforth some of these new wonders?\nReport on Taxes.\nAfter a year of study, the National\nIndustrial Conference Board has com\npleted a comprehensive report on tife\nsubject of State and local property\ntaxes.\nThe board has divided the report un?\nder two subjects: The various kinds of\ntaxes imposed and how they are ad\nministered.\nOs course, the first essential of any\ntax system Is that it should be enforce\nable. Many ideal forms of taxes seem\nto be non-enforceable, which Is a fatal\nweakness. Looking Into the future, the\nboard concludes that from the present\ntrend the future tax systems will In\nclude those imposed upon real estate\nand upon such tangible personal prop\nerty that has been found to be taxable,\nwhile the major part of the Intangible*\nwill be exempt and the property taxo*\nwill be supplemented by taxes upon\nother evidences of ability to pay, such\nas, for Instance, Income, Inheritance,\nbusiness and sales of certain selected\ncommodities.\nThe conference board concludes that\nthe State Tax Commission In every\nState should be made the Important\nbody to which the State Legislature\nshould turn for advice on tax matters.\nFor \"a poor law, well administered, may\nresult In an equitable tax system. A\ngood law, poorly administered, cannot\nDroduce satisfactory results.\u201d\nSugar Price Stabilization.\nThomas L. Chadboume, New York\nlawyer and financier, has been able to\nget the Cuban government to set aaidp\n$42,000,000 of borrowed money for this\nNational Sugar Export Corporation,\nwhich will enable te to purchase 1,500,-\n000 tons of Cuban sugar and withdraw\nIt from the market.\nThe corporation has wide powers,\nalmost dictatorial In sweep, both in the\nfield of production and export. The\nmoney will come from a loan which\nhas been negotiated privately, but\nwhich later may be offered publicly In\nthe United States.\nIf it is, President Hoover will find\nhimself in an embarrassing situation.\nAs a member of the Coolldge cabinet\nhe prevented American loans being\nmade to Brazil and Germany for the\nsame purpose\u2014price stabilization.\nIn the meantime, Mr. Chadboume U\non his way to Amsterdam to confer\nwith the Java sugar producers, who are\nup against world sugar overproduction.\nWill they join hands with Cuba? If\nthey agree to the plan, then the rest at\nthe world will be asked to join.\nIt Is an ambitious program. World\nrestriction In the cases of rubber, cop\nper and coffee have been a fizzle. What\nabout sugar? Perhaps this will be the\nexception.\nChadboume\u2019* Career.\nMr. Chadboume has been carrying\non these negotiations almost single--\nhanded. He was bom at Houghton,\nMich., 59 years ago. For a year he\nattended the University of Michigan,\nbut did not graduate. He was admit\nted to tfie bar In 1892, and began hit\nlaw practice In Milwaukee, Wis. Three\nyears later he moved to Chicago, and\nshortly thereafter to New York Otty.\nMr. Chadboume Is a giant of a man,\nwith a round, florid face. He Is pleas\nant, a good mixer, and the legal repre\nsentative of many of the larger indus\ntrial corporations. He was once chair\nman of the Democratic State Commit\ntee of New York Btate, and one of thi\nfinancial backers, with Bernard Baruclfc\nof Woodrow Wilson\u2019s campaign for the\npresidency.\nNew Financing SmalL\nThe sum of $165,000,000, the amount\nof new real estate bond, note and stock\nfinancing In the United States during\nthe first 10 months of 1930, represents\nthe lowest level In seven years\u2014a de\ncline of 67 per cent under the first 10\nmonths of 1929, and 78 per cent undo\n1928.\nGreat and drastic reduction In build\ning construction 1* the answer.\nnm fliHcnm r*","height":"25404","width":"19677"}}
